Q.1 What is JSX?

JSX is a special way of writing code in React. It looks like HTML but actually runs inside JavaScript.
Think of it as a shortcut that lets you mix HTML-like tags with JavaScript logic. Many people say it
stands for "JavaScript XML," but React’s official docs call it a "syntax extension for JavaScript."
In simple words: JSX makes writing UI code easier and more readable, but under the hood it’s still
JavaScript.

---

Q.2 Transpilation v/s Compilation

Transpilation: This means converting code from one version of a language to another. For example,
turning JSX into plain JavaScript, or ES6 (modern JS) into ES5 (older JS). It’s like translating
English into simpler English so more people can understand.

Compilation: This means converting human-readable code into machine-friendly code. For example,
bundling and minifying your project so the browser can run it faster. It’s like turning a recipe
into a ready-made dish.

---

Q.3 What is Babel?

Babel is a tool (a transpiler) that takes modern JavaScript and JSX code and changes it into older
JavaScript that all browsers can understand. Without Babel, many browsers would not know how to run
new features. Think of Babel as a translator that makes sure your code works everywhere.

---

Q.4 What Happens with JSX behind the scene?

1. Babel Transpiles JSX → React.createElement:
   JSX is not real HTML. Babel converts it into React.createElement calls. This is just JavaScript
   function calls that create virtual DOM elements.

2. Babel Transpiles ES6+ → ES5:
   If you use modern JS features (like arrow functions, async/await), Babel also converts them into
   older JS for compatibility.

3. Bundler Compilation (Webpack, Vite, etc.):
   All the transpiled files are bundled into one optimized file. This step is closer to compilation
   because it prepares your project for execution.

4. Browser Execution:
   React.createElement builds virtual DOM objects. React compares them (diffing) and updates only
   the parts of the real DOM that changed. This makes React fast and efficient.

---

Q.5 Why we use double curly braces in style attribute?

In JSX, inline styles are written as JavaScript objects, not strings. The first curly brace tells
React: “I’m writing JavaScript inside JSX.” The second curly brace is the actual object with style
properties. Example:

<div style={{ color: "red", fontSize: "20px" }}></div>

---

Q.6 Why we need to use className, htmlFor instead of class and for in JSX?

In JavaScript, “class” and “for” are reserved keywords. If JSX used them directly, it would cause
errors. That’s why React uses alternatives:
- className → replaces “class”
- htmlFor → replaces “for”
This avoids conflicts and makes JSX safe to compile.

---

Q.7 className is attribute or props in JSX?

className looks like an HTML attribute because we write it inside tags. But JSX is just JavaScript.
When Babel transpiles it, className becomes a prop passed to the React element. React then uses this
prop to set the actual HTML “class” attribute in the DOM. So technically, className is a prop in JSX.

---

Q.8 JSX doesn’t support loop like “for”, but we can use “map”. Why?

- “for” is a statement. It doesn’t return a value, so JSX can’t directly use it.
- “map” is an expression. It returns an array of elements, which JSX can render.

Example:
{items.map(item => <li>{item}</li>)}

This works because map produces values (elements) that React can display.

